“Once you start getting serious, you start seeing results.” I heard a version of this quote from someone at my last Weight Watchers meeting, and I feel as though it parallels so many different situations in life. If you commit to something, you will see progress as a result of hard work. I learned this the hard way two and a half years ago when I realized that I would have to “get serious” if I really wanted to make a change in my life.

&nbsp;

I was your stereotypical overweight girl before I finally decided to take the reins on my life. Along with teetering on the morbidly obese BMI sector, I was also experiencing high blood pressure and a low HDL count (the type of cholesterol you want to have a high level of because it helps you fight heart disease). I was not, by any means, physically fit. Of course I had the typical “fitness stints” in my life that never lasted more than six months at a time. Not only were my genes not on my side, but my mind was not on my side either. I relied on food for comfort, for stability, and for love; unfortunately, what I got in return was slowly wreaking havoc on my body at the youthful age of 21. What I ate in private certainly showed in public, and I was neither happy nor proud of that fact.

&nbsp;

Fast-forward to two and a half years ago, when a conversation with my doctor about my health issues really resonated with me. I was only 21 years old and already experiencing health concerns that are typically seen among the older population. I did not want to continue living my life for food; I wanted to live my life for LIFE. I finally decided to make the change and “get serious” about losing weight, so I joined Weight Watchers in 2012. To date, I have lost over 100 pounds by changing my diet and my lifestyle. I am an active gym-goer and runner. I have run multiple 5Ks and love the feeling of success I get from completing each one. I have gone from not feeling confident in my own skin, losing my breath at the simplest of tasks, and avoiding any activity that required physical effort to finally beginning to feel confident in who I am, finding my strength through pushing myself physically, and enjoying my life with the people I love and care about. Not only do I hope to serve as an inspiration and motivation to the important people in my life, but I hope to serve as a role model for anyone who is struggling with losing weight, because I truly believe that if I can overcome my biggest demon, anyone can.

&nbsp;

After losing the amount of weight that I have and learning and adapting a completely new lifestyle, I knew that it was time to share my thoughts and ideas with the world, which is why I started blogging. You can check out my personal blog at <a href="http://www.cake-sweat.com">Cake Sweat</a>, where I post my struggles, my successes, and everything in-between. I always appreciate any and all support I get from my readers, and I hope to support them in the same way. If you’d like to learn more about my story, I’d love it if you’d give it a read!

&nbsp;

This may seem like a fairy-tale success, but two and a half years on the same program can get boring, especially if you’re me. I had been tracking so long that it was becoming redundant, and I was no longer seeing the changes that I had wanted to see as far as my weight loss goals were concerned. I constantly thrive for new, exciting, and different, and at this point in my life, I was ready for a change. I knew I still wanted to be a Weight Watcher, but I wanted to try something new. I wasn’t losing any more weight; I was in the dreaded rut phase where my body was riding a roller coaster of gains and losses. I could feel my motivation slipping, and that’s when I knew it was time to try something else.

&nbsp;

After doing some research on the Paleo diet, I wanted to try it for myself. However, I was still toying with the idea because I wasn’t sure if I was ready to commit to a lifestyle free of processed foods. Our fast-paced world can make it extremely difficult to maintain a processed-free lifestyle, especially when people are always looking for convenience and speed; food choices being no different. I wasn’t sure if I would be successful, and I was a little hesitant to plunge right in. Fate stepped in when I saw a post online for a Paleo 30-day challenge group, and I took that as a sign. I would try the Paleo diet.

&nbsp;

For 30 days, I was strict Paleo. I really loved how it seemed to be the perfect marriage of two lifestyles: Paleo and Weight Watchers. With Paleo, I was being taught what types of foods to eat while being able to still maintain appropriate, healthy, portion-controlled meals through the Weight Watchers program. It was a perfect balance of healthy choices and smart sizes. I would still be able to use my Weight Watchers “app” and resources to determine the right amount of food, and utilize the basics of the Paleo diet to figure out what foods would be the best choices for me.

&nbsp;

Meal planning was important for me when doing Paleo, mainly because I knew that it was going to be difficult to figure out what foods I needed to eliminate from my diet that I was so used to having. I have to give up my beloved Chobani? I wasn’t too happy about that! Needless to say, grocery shopping and meal prepping was not something I looked forward to in the beginning. I never really knew just how processed everything is until reading about this diet. While on the diet, I used <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Practical-Paleo-Customized-Whole-Foods-Lifestyle/dp/1936608758"><em>Practical Paleo</em></a> by Diane Sanfilipo as a guide. This book is an easy read, and even provides tear-out guides to all things Paleo so you can have the foundation at your fingertips. I highly suggest using this book if you are considering the Paleo lifestyle. It lays out the plan so that you can start it right away without having to spend a lot of time reading up on it beforehand.

&nbsp;

There were a lot of benefits that I reaped from the diet. I definitely noticed a change in my sugar levels. I am occasionally prone to bouts of light-headedness, particularly during periods of time that I fluctuate between eating raw versus processed foods. The Paleo diet eliminated most of that feeling, simply due to the fact that I had cut out almost all processed foods entirely. Another benefit came from my doctor. While only two and a half weeks on the program, I had a yearly physical with my doctor, who had said that my triglyceride level (a test that determines the level of your LDL, which is what determines whether you have high cholesterol) was low, which is ideal. My triglyceride level was at 45 MG, while a normal level is less than 100 MG. She had said that it was rare for her to see a patient’s level this low, and that it was probably due to my elimination of processed foods. It was definitely a shock; I knew that processed foods wreak havoc on your body, but I didn’t realize how much my body was affected by it until this appointment.

&nbsp;

There were some times that I may have gotten off-plan during those 30 days, and I say “may” because I’m honestly not sure. Sometimes it’s so difficult to control your food environment that you just have to try your best and hope you’re doing it right. Many times I questioned my food when I went out to eat. Going out to eat is not typically recommended on the Paleo diet, but I did it anyways. I just made sure to read the menu, ask questions, and attempt to get my food as plainly prepared as possible. When in doubt, ask for gluten-free options. Be prepared for some strange looks from the waiters when asking for specific ingredients of certain dishes—it's like they think you’re trying to steal their recipes or something!

&nbsp;

As much as I loved the lifestyle as a whole, I knew that it wasn’t something I could fully commit to 100% of the time for the rest of my life. I still follow many of the guidelines on the Paleo diet, but I’ve learned to incorporate it into my own lifestyle that works for me. I still eat lots of fresh fruits and vegetables, and I try to consume protein sources through eggs, chicken, and seafood. If I do buy processed foods, I try to buy gluten-free as often as possible, with as little ingredients on the label as I can find. (On a sidenote-I am a huge fan of the Enjoy Life products for gluten-free options, especially their chocolate chips. Talk about an indulgence without the guilt!) I also try to stay away from any processed fat and dairy, such as margarine and skim milk, and stick to butter and almond milk if I’m looking for substitutions. Even though the full commitment isn’t for me, the core ideas behind the Paleo diet have really taught me how to properly fuel my body.

&nbsp;

Since this was a total lifestyle change for me, I had to find creative ways to make some of the foods that I loved “Paleo-approved.” I’m a dessert girl at heart, so of course I had to find ways to get in a little sweet treat every once in a while!

&nbsp;

Here’s a recipe for one of my quick and easy desserts, and I think it pairs well with the change of season and the availability of this delicious fruit!

&nbsp;

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Paleo Apple Crumble</strong></span>
<img src="http://i58.tinypic.com/2wel6s3.jpg" alt="" width="214" height="286" />

Ingredients:
<ul>
	<li>1-2 apples, peeled and diced</li>
	<li>2 tablespoons Bob’s Red Mill Organic, High-Fiber Coconut Flour</li>
	<li>1-2 tablespoons water</li>
	<li>Cinnamon, nutmeg, brown sugar to taste</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

Directions:
<ol>
	<li>Place the apples in a microwave-safe bowl.</li>
	<li>Microwave on high for two minutes.</li>
	<li>Take the bowl out of the microwave and stir the apples.</li>
	<li>Microwave on high for another two minutes.</li>
	<li>While it is microwaving the second time, place the coconut flour and one tablespoon of the water in a bowl. Mix with a fork until it resembles a crumble mixture. Add more water if needed, one teaspoon at a time.</li>
	<li>Add in your spices to the crumble mixture to taste.</li>
	<li>Top the apples with the crumble mixture.</li>
	<li>Enjoy!</li>
</ol>
&nbsp;

