BREAKING NEWS: “Internet and social media overreaction turns breakfast into the least important meal of the day.”

&nbsp;

Whoa, whoa, whoa. Let’s ease up. Yes, some recent research calls into question the absolute certainty of the famous statement “Breakfast is the most important meal of the day.” But it’s a problem when people take <a href="http://www.outsideonline.com/fitness/bodywork/performance-plate/Breakfast-Schmeakfast.html">mild questioning</a> and turn it into a wholehearted indictment of something, such as the early-morning meal that many athletes need for optimal performance.

&nbsp;

Athletes, mind you. Beasts. If we’re talking about everyday people who care more about run-of-the-mill weight loss than anything else, it might be a different story. But finely tuned athletes need the right <a href="https://www.amrapnutrition.com/">Paleo fuel</a> for their machine-like efforts.

&nbsp;

Of course, every <a href="http://www.crossfit.com/">CrossFit</a> athlete is different. No two people have the exact same body composition, schedule and lifestyle. Thus, it’s impossible to lump everyone into one category when it comes to <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/john-berardi-phd/breakfast-health_b_4436439.html">breakfast</a>.

&nbsp;

Rather than constantly weighing one scientific study vs. another and another, try asking your body the answer to the great breakfast debate. There are several key factors to consider, including:
<ul>
	<li>Do you usually wake up hungry?</li>
	<li>What time of day do you normally work out?</li>
	<li>Do you perform better with a recently fueled body?</li>
	<li>Do you participate in <a href="http://www.precisionnutrition.com/intermittent-fasting">intermittent fasting</a>?</li>
	<li>Does your body respond better to several small meals or a couple large meals on a daily basis?</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

Again, it’s about your body, not about a glut of Internet chatter. Do you think our ancestors sat around worrying about what time of day to eat? They ate when their bodies screamed out “Feed me!”

&nbsp;

Let’s not get hung up on recipes, either. If breakfast is important to you, then anything from <a href="http://www.pinterest.com/pin/86412886571191655/">inventive pancakes</a> to <a href="http://crossfitfenrir.com/quick-paleo-breakfast-options/">protein-packed bites</a> can get the job done.

&nbsp;

Should athletes eat breakfast? Yes — if their bodies ask for it.

Addiction is a difficult enemy to fight regardless of your age. Once you become dependant on alcohol or drugs it seems impossible to quit your daily fix that gives you some sort of temporary relief. It starts innocently enough with a couple of drinks with friends and before you know it, you are drinking almost every other day! Let us find out how <strong>CrossFit</strong> acted as a catalyst in fashioning an alcoholic into a changed individual.

&nbsp;
<h3><strong>Who is Adam Huston?</strong></h3>
No he isn’t a celebrity or someone famous- he is an ordinary guy who became addicted to drinking like thousands of others worldwide. He was just like any other person, looking for a good time with his friends. Before long, he was drinking all the time regardless of the occasion. Getting arrested for drinking and driving had become a common occurrence for him. However, he realized that he was basically throwing his life away, especially since a couple of his family members have a bad history when it comes to drinking. He didn’t want to check into a rehab to combat his addiction – he chose a different way to deal with it. <strong>CrossFit </strong>was the perfect answer to his problems.

&nbsp;
<h3><strong>How CrossFit helped him?</strong></h3>
Enrolling in <strong>CrossFit</strong> completely changed his outlook on life and made him into a stronger and more confident person. He lost almost 23 pounds and even though the grueling routines were tough at first, he slowly began to get the hang of it. The turning point is when he came to terms with the fact that drinking wasn’t the right way to channel his emotions as it would hamper his health. The beauty of <strong>CrossFit</strong> is that the exercises are not just devised to target physical fitness but also ensure peace of mind at the same time. You learn to sharpen focus on life and work, be more alert, and don’t let stress bring you down. It allowed Adam to emerge from what he calls his “dark place” as a person who is ready to take on life as it comes. To put it in a nutshell, he is healthy and happy now. <a href="http://vimeo.com/103475356" target="_blank">Watch his full story here.</a>

&nbsp;

You don’t need to an excuse to try <strong>CrossFit</strong> – there is no right time or a specific reason as to why you should enroll. It has helped to shape the body and mind of thousands of individuals all over the world, so it can work wonders for you as well. If you are interested to find out more about CrossFit, do take a look at these <a href="https://www.amrapnutrition.com/blog/">articles</a> for some inspiration. It is a guarantee you will not be disappointed!

