You might have come across the term GMO quite frequently these days. In fact, there have been several programs launched to implement bans on products that contain GMOs. For instance, you can spot critics around the farmers market urging people to buy GMO free products only. Learn what to know about GMOs.

&nbsp;

<strong>What are GMOs?</strong>

The term GMO indicates genetically modified organisms, whose genetic structure or DNA had been changed artificially in a laboratory with the aid of genetic engineering techniques. This scientific method was developed in order to conceptualize combinations of plant, bacteria, viral, and animal genes that don’t occur naturally or via traditional crossbreeding. Needless to say, this combination is unstable.

&nbsp;

<strong>What is the risk?</strong>

In most countries, GMOs are considered to be harmful, which is why there have been restrictions or complete bans on production and sale of products with GMOs in them. Individuals have become more conscious so they wish to know if they are consuming food with GMOs in them, but the labels might not contain accurate information in this case. In 2012, a poll by the Mellman Group clearly stated that 91% of American consumers wanted to know via labels about the presence of GMOs. Some even went on to say that they would switch diets if they discovered that the food chain has been tampered with. Long term effects of such products on the human body are still not known.

&nbsp;

<strong>What is the Non-GMO Project?</strong>

It is a non-profit organization that is dedicated towards providing consumers with an informed choice and also protecting the non-GMO food products. Their objective is to educate people so that they stop buying GMO laden foods from the markets, which in turn will force the companies from marketing them and farmers from producing them at all. The Non-GMO Project’s seal for verified products will be a 100% guarantee that there is no GMO.

&nbsp;

<strong>What remains to be done?</strong>

In spite of organizations working hard to make people aware about GMOs, most individuals shopping at farmers markets or department stores don’t even know what those initials stand for, let alone being informed about the harm they cause. Before any kind of change is made, it is necessary to ensure that the majority of the American population knows about the problem, after which they can work towards implementing the solution.

&nbsp;

