There is no particular occasion to gobble up some yummy and delicious candy, right? It is popular among all ages because no one likes to resist these tasty <a href="https://www.amrapnutrition.com/?p=1461" target="_blank">sugar treats</a>. But can we actually classify this as a “treat”. These facts about the sugar industry from John Oliver will shock you and have you rethinking your <a href="https://www.amrapnutrition.com/?p=1461" target="_blank">grocery list</a>!

&nbsp;

<strong>Take a look:</strong>

<strong> </strong>
<ul>
	<li>An American consumes 22 teaspoons sugar per day on an average, which is 3 times more than what the body needs. The total goes up to 75 pounds of sugar every year.</li>
	<li>Rovenia Brock, a nutritionist states that sugar is put in various kinds of food such as ketchup, crackers, salad dressings, breads, cereals, sports and energy drinks, and many more.</li>
	<li>The World Health Organization and American Heart Association have issued repeated warnings about the harmful effects of ingesting more sugar than what is required. It has been known to mess with the functionality of the brain.</li>
	<li>Andy Briscoe, the president of the Sugar Association has stated that sugar doesn’t have any bearing on diabetes or obesity – a fact that is completely untrue. While sugar might not be the only ingredient responsible for those conditions, it certainly contributes to them. Scientists are openly claiming that sugar and obesity are unrelated, but that is mostly because they are on the payroll of some top honchos in the industry and don’t want to lose their retainers!</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

<strong>What is FDA doing?</strong>

&nbsp;

Oliver says that while the effects of sugar might still be debatable, consumers have a right to know when it is being added to their food. We couldn’t agree more. Food should be transparent. The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has proposed changes to nutrition labels by mentioning “added sugars” as a separate category, but have been bombarded with letters from every conceivable product in the food industry. If the changes were to take place, it would be extremely beneficial to consumers as they would know exactly how much sugar is in the product. Trouble is they are not likely to go through with it.

&nbsp;

The American Beverage Association wrote to the FDA that if there is an “added sugars” category, the quantity should be mentioned in grams and not in teaspoons. Although the association claims that a measurement in teaspoons will confuse people, it is indeed an underhanded attempt to divert consumers from understanding whether the quantity of sugar in the product will be detrimental to their health.

&nbsp;

On a funny note, Oliver claims that the sugar content should be listed in terms of circus peanuts, which taste absolutely horrible! But you, don’t need us telling you about it. See for yourself.

